I'll give you a breakdown of American education. The United States is a federal republic that can be found in North America. It has a population of about 328 million and is renowned for its rich cultural heritage. Although English is the official language, the entire nation also speaks a variety of other languages. K-12 Education System: In the United States, state and local governments are primarily in charge of overseeing and funding the K–12 education system. The system consists of primary and secondary education, with the former covering kindergarten through grade five and the latter covering grades six through twelve. States and districts have different curricula and standards, but math, science, English, social studies, and foreign languages are generally prioritized. Various school types, including traditional public schools, charter schools, and private schools, are also included in the educational system. The achievement gap—a persistent disparity in academic achievement and educational opportunities between various groups of students, particularly those from low-income families and students of color—is one of the main concerns in the United States. Major educational policies and initiatives: A federal law known as the No Child Left Behind Act (NCLB) was passed in 2001 with the intention of enhancing academic achievement and holding schools responsible for pupil performance. The law has drawn criticism for its emphasis on standardized testing and its dearth of funding for underperforming schools. As a replacement for NCLB, the Every Student Succeeds Act (ESSA) was enacted in 2015. It aims to give states and districts more latitude in how they improve schools and close the achievement gap. Schools with high percentages of low-income students are eligible for federal funding under Title I of the Elementary and Secondary Education Act (ESEA). By giving resources and support to schools that most need it, this funding aims to reduce the achievement gap. Low-income children and their families can receive comprehensive early childhood education, health, nutrition, and parent involvement services through the Head Start program. Overall, there are ongoing efforts to enhance student outcomes and address disparities in the diverse and complex American educational system. The achievement gap is still a major concern, and policymakers and educators are still working to find solutions. 